#Makes 2 Overflowing Gratins
#Ingredients
* 1/2 stick (1/4 cup or 4 tbsp) butter, preferably unsalted
* 2 large yellow onions, chopped for ~4 cups
* 1/4 cup of flour
* 1/4 tsp grated nutmeg
* 1 cup heavy cream
* 2 cups milk
* 5 - 10 ounce boxes frozen spinach; defrost in fridge the night before cooking and open and put in colandar 3 hours before prepping
* 1 cup Parmesan cheese, grated and divided into 2 aliquots of 1/2 cup each. 
* 1 tbsp Kosher salt
* 1/2 tsp ground black pepper
* 1/2 cup grated Gruyere cheese, preferably smoked and Zupan's carries it

#Equipment: 
* At least 2 medium sized gratin dishes, each holding approximately 18-20 ozs.
* Large colander and plate to rest it on
* Optional but highly recommended: metal cookie sheet and aluminum foil.

#Instructions
* 1. The night before making, defrost the spinach in the fridgerator. 3 hours before starting to cook, open the packages and drain spinach in a colandar on a plate, occasionally dumping water out of the plate.
* 2. Preheat oven to 400 degrees CONVECTION if using a good oven; otherwise preheat to 425 degrees.
* 2. In a LeCreuset heavy dutch oven, melt the butter over medium heat.
* 3. Add onions and saute until translucent--anywhere from 2 - 20 minutes depending on which coast you buy them!
* 4. Add flour and nutmeg, and cook and stir continuously for 2 minutes.
* 5. Add cream and milk, and cook and stir continuously until thickened.
* 6. Using hands, squeeze water out of the spinach and then add the spinach to the cream mixture. 
* 7. Add 1/2 cup of parmesan to the spinach, reserving other 1/2 cup of parmesan. Mix very well, then add salt and pepper.
* 8. Turn off the heat.
* 9. Cover the cookie sheet with aluminum foil, and place the gratin dishes on top.
*10. Transfer mixture to the gratin dishes, making sure there is enough room left to sprinkle cheese on top.
*11. Sprinkle the reserved Parmesan cheese and the Gruyere cheese on top.
*12. Bake for 20 minutes, until hot and bubbly.
*13. These can be assembled and placed in the fridge for a few hours before baking.
